\begin_layout Section
Intro
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Portal is a video game released in 2007 by Valve Software,
 and it was a very influential game for video game design.
 As a puzzle game,
 it is very important that it teaches its workings to the players,
 so that they understand all the pieces they will need and how to put them together.
 The game is widely considered to do so rather well,
 with a lot of development time being spent in addressing this matter,
 and in a bold move,
 especially for the time,
 spends a lot of game time explaining the mechanics – it's said that about 50% of the game is tutorial,
 which was quite revolutionary,
 as a lot of games at the time had really short and crummy tutorials and a lot of people would just skip past them because they were boring...
 And yet,
 Portal players would spend approximately 3 hours of game time playing a tutorial,
 often not even noticing it for what it was.
 Surely there is a big parallel to be drawn here!
 Like...
 The best type of teaching is when people don't realize they're being taught?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
A note on why video games generally are a good topic to talk about here:
 Most types of media definitely care about the person consuming the media understanding the material,
 but in no other type of media is there so much incentive to hyperoptimize teaching.
 Like,
 sure,
 books and movies want you to understand the plot...
 But this is mostly 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

fact-type knowledge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 you won't be solving any problems with this data (unless you're the type to try to figure out the ending before it happens,
 in which case the onus is on you and doesn't use any 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

type of knowledge
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 new to you from the book),
 and even if there are problems to solve and you don't,
 the medium proceeds anyway...
 Indeed,
 no other type of mainstream medium is 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

understanding-locked
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 like a puzzle game would be – if you don't understand how to solve the puzzle,
 you don't advance.
 In a sense,
 math classes occupy the worst middle ground:
 If you don't understand the math,
 you shouldn't be advancing,
 but the quarter proceeds regardless.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
Now,
 let's discuss incentives.
 In math classes,
 the student has a strong incentive to put in effort because if they fail that's bad for their future.
 For a video game it's like...
 If you're not having fun,
 you get up and go play something else,
 worst case you just wasted $60 of your parent's money,
 whatever.
 And if you don't like it,
 probably other people don't like it,
 and the game is going to get bad reviews and not make a lot of money.
 And if that weren't enough incentive to optimize for the player experience,
 you also have a fact that doesn't occur in math classrooms (aside from specialized contexts like video-recordings):
 When designing the first 5 levels for a game,
 you're designing something that'll be experienced – verbatim,
 without change – by thousands or millions of players.
 It is worth putting hundreds and thousands of person-hours into making this as seamless as an experience as it can be;
 unlike when designing the first class for a course,
 where,
 if it doesn't go that well,
 whatever,
 you'll do better next time...
 The diminishing returns kick in very early for experiences that will be seen by only ~30 people.
\end_layout

