\begin_layout Section
Discussion
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
I don't have that much to say that hasn't been said already.
 I really like this game,
 and the tightness of the first few minutes is a big reason for it.
 The developers later went on to release a sequel,
 Portal 2,
 in 2011,
 which had just as much design wisdom packed into it – but it takes longer to get started,
 so would not have been as adequate for a pedagogy seminar.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
These same developers also released a bunch of other games,
 mostly shooters.
 And yet,
 even in those games,
 where maybe you would expect design not to matter as much (pew pew doesn't require that much thought),
 they still managed to make them very seamless experiences through very smart and calculated decisions.
 Example:
 Team Fortress 2,
 a shooter game that looks like this:
 (Show picture of tf2)
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
In this game,
 there are nine distinct classes that one can play as,
 and against.
 One's reactions when seeing a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

heavy
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 should be very different than seeing a 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

demoman
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

:
 The heavy has this gun,
 which shoots bullets,
 so you want to get away from him or get into a place with lots of cover;
 the demoman can only fight through grenades that are hard to aim up close but give him indirect fire,
 so you want to get up in his face,
 somewhere without cover,
 and preferably with height advantage.
 As such,
 since these decisions must be made in a split-second,
 it's very important to know at a glance what type of opponent you're up against.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
