\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
The point is that the developers prioritized what information they wanted to convey,
 and calculated how efficiently different modes of visual communication convey this information,
 and matched the most important data to the most visually distinct method.
 The silhouette point is more striking than it seems:
 Many shooters back then and now opt for a realistic type of visual,
 where,
 well,
 mostly every human looks the same.
 But in designing this game to look cartoonish,
 they gave themselves the opportunity to design visually distinct silhouettes,
 which aids the players in understanding at a very quick glance what type of enemy they're up against.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
These developers aren't unique,
 of course – though they're definitely a couple of standard deviations above the mean,
 and the fact that they've released 13 critically acclaimed games since 2004 is a testament to the fact that they 
\emph on
are
\emph default
 good at their job.
 But there are a lot more designers out there making a lot more games that have just as much thought and effort put into them as these games did,
 and honestly,
 I think there's probably more stuff that can be learned from them.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Point
One more thing on video games:
 One benefit that they have,
 in terms of designability,
 relative to math classes,
 is that they can afford to have dozens of people play their game (being paid to do so) and modify the material in the face of that.
 Moreover,
 these people are trained in playtesting – knowing how to play games in the way that is most useful from the perspective of generating feedback for developers...
 and I suppose you could kind of do that for math,
 to train 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

reverse classroom playtesters
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

,
 but it'd be pretty difficult for someone to learn calculus for the 10th time whilst retaining the perspective of someone new to the subject (while every playtester playing a new game does have roughly the mindset of someone new to that game,
 because most games do not have exactly the same mechanics as other games).
 Anyway,
 right now the best we have,
 I think,
 is having people who already know the material we're teaching look over our material through the eyes of someone they're modeling in their head,
 who does not already know the material,
 which is very imperfect,
 and alternatively having test subjects go through whatever material we've designed,
 even though if it's poorly designed they're the ones who end up underprepared,
 and just having to rely on their imperfect feedback (they don't necessarily know what the endgoal is...) to enact modifications for the next iteration.
\end_layout

